Reading inputs looks trivial — read the **input data register (IDR)** — but real mechanical contacts and edge-triggered interrupts add rigor.

**Debouncing.** A mechanical switch does not make one clean transition; the contacts bounce for ~1–20 ms, producing a burst of edges. On a scope you'll see a ragged transition; an edge interrupt will fire many times. Schmitt-trigger inputs (built into most GPIO) clean *slow analog* noise via hysteresis but do **not** fix contact bounce. Two cures: **hardware** (RC filter + Schmitt, or an RS-latch) and **software** (sample periodically and accept a change only after N consecutive stable reads, or ignore further edges for a guard time).

```c
/* Integrator debounce: call every ~1 ms from a timer ISR. */
static uint8_t hist = 0xFF;
static uint8_t stable = 1;

uint8_t debounce(uint8_t raw_high) {
    hist = (uint8_t)((hist << 1) | (raw_high & 1u));
    if (hist == 0x00) stable = 0;       /* 8 stable lows  */
    else if (hist == 0xFF) stable = 1;  /* 8 stable highs */
    return stable;                       /* else: still bouncing */
}
```

**EXTI — external interrupts.** Instead of polling, an EXTI line can fire on a pin event. You choose the sensitivity:

- **Edge-triggered** — rising, falling, or both. Fires once per transition; the canonical choice for a button or a sensor data-ready pulse.
- **Level-triggered** — active as long as the line is at a level. Re-asserts immediately if you return while the level persists, so it suits a held condition but risks an interrupt storm if not cleared/handled.

For EXTI you still configure the pin (clock + input + pull), then route the line to the EXTI controller, select edge sensitivity, unmask it, and enable the IRQ in the NVIC. In the ISR, **clear the pending flag** — forget it and you re-enter forever. Keep the ISR short: set a `volatile` flag, defer the work.
